narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: A fundamental overview of the theory behind aerodynamics. Skills to calculate and analyze properties related to airfoils.
I worked a lot in theoretical math and got a better understanding of fluid dynamics and the basics of aerodynamic theory.
I feel like I've gained an intuitive sense of aerodynamic design and I learned a lot about how different supersonic flows are to subsonic flows.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: This course is very engaging and moves through a wide range of material quite quickly. The material is very interesting and goes much beyond the scope of fluids.

Strengths: The class is usually pretty small so you get a lot of one-on-one time with the professor and it is generally pretty flexible. Exams are very similar to practice exams so there are limited surprises on test days (although this doesn't necessarily make the exams easier). Weaknesses: The class is somewhat disorganized, and the notes sheets aren't incredibly helpful to understand concepts. The class tends to be focused very deeply in the theory without many attempts to contextualize the theory in a way that makes sense for students.

I think that the lecture notes are great, they are very concise. One issue is that sometimes Professor de la Mora can explain things very quickly and act like the topics are very intuitive, even though aerodynamics is far from intuitive. This was not an issue as long as I read the lecture notes closely before or after lectures, though.

Another great aspect of the course was the use of Mathematica. I think a lot of engineering courses focus too much on theory and mathematics and do not use enough computational tools (which is what is being done in actual engineering).

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend this to anyone with a good background in fluids and an interest in aerodynamics. You should be prepared to dedicate a good amount to the material.

I would likely only recommend this course to students who were very interested in specifically airplane engineering and had a strong background in multivariable calculus and fluid dynamics. Its a very interesting course, but the amount of work necessary to get an understanding of the material is likely more than is reasonable for most students.
Yes, I absolutely loved the content of the course.
